  "prompt": "Does blind person from birth dream?",
  "response": "Yes, blind people from birth do dream. However, their dreams are different from those of sighted people:\n\n1. Visual Dreams:\n- People blind from birth do not have visual imagery in their dreams\n- Their dreams are composed of other sensory experiences like sound, touch, taste, and smell\n\n2. Brain Processing:\n- The brain adapts to process sensory information differently\n- Dreams are formed using non-visual sensory experiences they encounter in daily life\n\n3. Scientific Research:\n- Studies show that congenitally blind people have dreams rich in sounds, emotions, and spatial awareness\n- Their dream experiences are just as complex and meaningful as those of sighted individuals\n\n4. Brain Activity:\n- Brain scans show similar dream-related brain activity in blind and sighted people\n- The primary difference is the absence of visual components\n\n5. REM Sleep:\n- Blind people experience REM (Rapid Eye Movement) sleep like sighted people\n- Their dreams occur during these same sleep stages\n\nSo while blind people from birth don't have visual dreams, they do have rich, vivid dreams using their other sensory experiences and imagination.",
